##The Battle of Wuhan: An unprecedented super-action

In the history of human fight against epidemic disease, "Wuhan Battle" has become an unprecedented super action

Battle of Wuhan

Our reporters Liu Yuanhang, Huang Xiaoguang, Li Mingzi

PUBLISHED: February 17,2020

At 3:00 a.m. , transfer vehicles from all the streets of Jianghan District stopped at the entrance to the Wuhan International Convention and Exhibition Center. This is the night of February 6, the temporary conversion of the Military Exhibition Shelter Hospital has just been completed, the community isolation point of some mild patients were transferred overnight here, to meet them, is just set up field medical team.

The rain never stopped. Wang Jun, a transfer driver on Tangjiadun street in Jianghan district, said his colleague, who was supposed to pick up only one patient, had 14 patients down from the quarantined hotel, working until 4 a.m. , when their protective clothing was drenched, has Lost its protective effect. Wang Jun took over and continued to take patients to the shelter hospital. As the day dawned, some of the patients did not meet the admission requirements, and some were not satisfied with the conditions inside, so he had to send them back the same way.

By the time the mission was over, it was 11:30 p.m. Wang Jun sat slumped in his Hazmat suit in the converted van. These days, he has been shuttling between the Shelter Hospital, the designated hospital and the community isolation point. Looking out of the car, he saw the National Emergency Medical Rescue Team's supply truck parked outside the shelter hospital. The patients with mild illness got out of the transfer vehicle. Each of them was carrying a large bag and a small bag, waiting for the medical staff to screen them.

It was a battle that had to be fought.

The sheer scarcity of medical resources, the growing number of confirmed cases, the safety risks of cross-infection, and the pervasive fear are all challenges ahead. Initially proposed by some scholars of comprehensive screening and hierarchical isolation, gradually became a social consensus, and eventually transformed into a super-action.

On January 27, Politburo member of the Communist Party of China Sun Chunlan, Vice Premier of the State Council, led a central guidance team to Wuhan, Hubei Province, to implement the deployment requirements of the Central Working Leading Group on the new coronavirus epidemic. On February 2, the Hubei Provincial Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters held a meeting and requested that all suspected patients be placed under centralized quarantine.

In just a few days, the document travels from the centre to the places, layers upon layers, to the nerve endings of the administrative system, to every street and community in Wuhan.

On 6 February, three shelter hospitals were renovated within two days and began receiving patients with confirmed mild illnesses. Soon, Wuhan announced that the number of shelter from the initial 3 to 15 rapid expansion. At the same time, the national strength has also been organized and mobilized, around the medical rescue team continuously rushed to Wuhan.

More than a month had passed since the initial outbreak. Many are watching to see if this top-down state action can create a level playing field in the ever-hectic battle for prevention and control and give the situation a chance to improve.

On the night of January 28, Li Guohua, a community security guard, used a small loudspeaker to call on residents to pay attention to safety and epidemic prevention in a community in Xiqiao community, Tangjiadun Street, Jianghan district, Wuhan. Photograph: Chen Zhuo for Changjiang daily

Zhang Wenhong, head of the Shanghai Medical Treatment Expert Group and Director of the hospital infection department at Mount Hua hospital, said the Wuhan Armageddon was just beginning. At present, the number of cases is still rising rapidly, and some of the patients are still undiagnosed and scattered outside. It is estimated that the prevention and control measures are really effective, it will take between one and two weeks after all patients have been admitted to the Mount Kinabalu hospitals and diagnosed under complete isolation. At that time, the epidemic plateau and inflection point can come. The outspoken clinical expert said it was "the darkest hour before the Dawn" .

Full mobilization

At the beginning of the interview, Zhou said he was "dying. ". He is the director of a community in Wuhan Qiao Estuary, in his early thirties. The community has only eight staff members to serve more than 10,000 residents. Property has not started, the community staff to pack everything, issued a protective clothing, but "thinner than paper" , usually only a mask. A day earlier, a confirmed patient, unable to get to a hospital, went to the community office, took off his mask, spat all over the place, and said he was going to die with them.

"I'm not afraid at all. I'd rather be infected. We may be able to handle it physically now, but we can't handle it mentally or psychologically. "I haven't had a day off in the New Year, and I'm on duty for the next 24 hours, and at this point, my body can't take it anymore, " Zhou told China News Weekly.

The Community of Fangyingtai, located on Fruit Lake Street in Wuchang District, had 15 workers before the outbreak. Around the time of the Spring Festival, everyone is still busy organizing various community Huimin County projects, including hundreds of family dinners and birthday parties for the elderly. After the outbreak of the epidemic, staff continued to decrease, either because of the closure of the home, unable to get in and out; some parents seriously ill, unable to get out; still others have symptoms of fever. Now, there are only seven people here who keep working.

With more than half of the staff gone, the community secretary had to take the lead in everything, including helping feverish residents into ambulances. On January 29, the community secretary was also infected and confined to his home. The pressure is all on Deputy Secretary Yu Juan. "Now the new cases are all suspected because there are confirmed cases at home, and the family members have also developed fever after intensive contact. But the problem is that the confirmed patients have no place to go and can not arrange hospitals,"Yu told China news weekly.

The shortage of hospital beds is the crux of the matter. Many residents try their best to keep in touch with each other, but a bed is still hard to find. A woman knocked a Gong on the balcony of the community, asking for help for her seriously ill mother, hoping to be admitted to the hospital. The video went viral on the Internet, and similar things happen every day in Wuhan.

In Yu's view, the chaotic order exacerbated the already tense situation. The process is not clear, and residents with fever are required to come to the community for a certificate, whether they are admitted to a hospital or diagnosed with a suspected case.

Ms. Yu said the community workers were "both parents. ". It is inevitable for us to be in Foshan community, which is the foundation of grid management and the First Line of defense for the prevention and control of infectious diseases. The grid management mode originated from the management experience of Shanghai in the fight against SARS in 2003. The specific approach is to divide the jurisdiction into several grids according to certain standards, through the grid inspection, supervision and proactive problem detection and timely processing.

Yu Juan also received the above under the "report to the public letter, " leaving a "888" beginning of the hotline. She used to trumpet the document in the community, saying to call the hotline if needed. But then residents complained that the number was either busy or in transit, and that it didn't work, and eventually it found its way to the community.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On Jan. 31, relatives of people suspected of new coronavirus infection were waiting for news by the side of the road on Xinhua road in Hankou, Wuhan. Photo / Yangtze daily, Kim sze-ryu

Grass-roots workers face, as well as the community residents in panic under the role of a variety of acts and reactions. Some suspected patients in isolation out of the hotel, secretly ran to the hospital for examination, the test results are fine, but said he was seriously ill, call the community at midnight to request the arrangement of vehicles, to pick him up. There are also many residents who had just the common cold, but insisted on going to designated hospitals for tests, the results were cross-infection.

Individual citizens have even more "strange" behavior. Although some elderly people live alone, but their children live in nearby communities, also require the community to buy food shopping for them, and even on the brand of goods have clear requirements, need to run several places to buy.

The plight of grass-roots communities is only a microcosm of Wuhan's epidemic prevention and control. The Designated Hospital in Wuhan, which is responsible for the treatment of critically ill patients, is already overcrowded and operating over capacity. What is more worrying is that medical staff continue to be infected and the situation of medical staff attrition is severe.

On January 22, the deputy director of Kam Yin Tam Hospital in Wuhan, Huang Chaolin, was diagnosed as new coronavirus pneumonia and is still being treated in isolation ward. Huang Zhaolin not only has been fighting in the front line of the fight against the epidemic, during the "Lancet" published an article, analyzed the Wuhan first batch of 41 cases of patients.

As of January 28,41.3 percent of the 138 patients in Wuhan University's Zhongnan Hospital were likely to have contracted the infection in the hospital, said Peng Zhiyong, director of ICU at the hospital, in the journal Jama, of the 57 cases of nosocomial infection, 40 were health care workers. In addition, according to a statistical chart displayed by emergency physician of the First People's Hospital of Guangzhou on his personal account, there have been more than 15 confirmed cases by health care workers in more than 10 hospitals in Wuhan. So far, the number of confirmed and suspected cases has exceeded 1,000.

"because there are four categories of people to be treated, there are a lot of patients in Wuhan Right now, and a lot of people are not being treated, including some elderly people who are lonely and widowed. It's a painful process to watch, and it's also why we feel so stressed,"Zheng Tianming, a Wuhan Union Hospital doctor, told China News weekly in a tearful voice, "hospitals started mobilizing physicians, and then a lot of physicians and nurses collapsed, and now they're mobilizing surgeons and nurses. "

Rome was built in less than two days

Had it not been for the outbreak, the Wembley Arena would have held the Asian Oceania boxing qualification at this time. But on February 3rd the Wembley Arena underwent a major transformation. A team of 15 from the Split Second, China's largest architectural design institute, started a renovation of the building. It's scheduled to open in two days. As time is too tight, they can only "design, construction, while adjusting. ".

On Feb. 1, Wang Chen, vice president of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, traveled to Wuhan to investigate. During the SARS epidemic in 2003, he served as Beijing's anti-sars Expert Group leader. After a survey in Wuhan, he found that most of the infections were clustered. In order to centralize and stratify admissions, ease the pressure on hospitals and communities, Wang Chen proposed building a "shelter hospital. ".

According to public information, the equipment of a shelter hospital is usually composed of a series of shelters with different medical or technical support functions and has the ability to carry out early treatment. Wang Chen said, the shelter hospital is a medical place, play a centralized treatment, isolation effect, patients can get basic medical care. "It is essential that all patients diagnosed with mild illness are promptly admitted for medical care, isolated from their families and society, and prevented from creating new sources of infection. "

The materials needed for reconstruction are huge and varied, ranging from power cables, square steel, light-duty fireproof boards, to nails, bolts and pipe bends, with different types and materials, basically need to transfer goods from different suppliers. In Wuhan, which has been sealed off, traffic control has made transport more difficult.

After the shelter hospital was built, six power distribution cabinets were needed to meet the electricity demand of all medical equipment and switch outlets in the three areas, but such a temporary configuration of power distribution cabinets was hard to find in the nearly shuttered city of Wuhan. Starting in the early hours of February 4, the people in charge called all the suppliers and tried every means to find the right parts in Ezhou, 100km away. Only after government co-ordination did they arrive at the construction site.

It took only 36 hours to renovate the Wuchang Shelter Hospital. When it was finished, medical personnel immediately began to move in. Shelter to 50 beds for a medical unit, such a pattern has been described as "chase shop" , many people worry about easy cross-infection. In response to this question, the National Health Commission later came out specifically to clarify that treatment is confirmed patients, there is no cross-infection.

A picture that had leaked from the Internet earlier showed the colorful sheets laid out by volunteers. After the volunteers left, 20 doctors from Hubei Provincial Cancer Hospital rushed into action, tucking in their quilts. "Our cancer hospital is responsible for 122 beds in total, and 200 sets of sterile quilts were distributed for uniform color, " Xie Rong, a member of the medical team of Hubei Provincial Cancer Hospital, told China News Weekly, it took them nearly two hours to make the bed again.

According to Xie, the Wuchang Shelter Hospital is divided into the West, east and basement. Taking the eastern shelter as an example, it is divided into clean area, semi-polluted area, polluted area and buffer area. After entering the patient's contaminated area from the clean area where the health-care workstation is located, the health-care workers are not allowed to take the "back road" , but must enter the buffer area from the other side and return to the clean area again.

"On the morning of February 5, there was nothing in the stadium. By the afternoon, it had taken on the shape of a hospital, " Xie said. At 11:30 that night, the Wuchang Shelter Hospital was put into service. At that time, the reporter saw outside the door, the hospital has received the first batch of patients in the western district, the entrance of a number of security guards to prevent patients from entering.

The Wuchang Shelter Hospital is run by the "national medical team + Wuhan Medical Team" , with the People's Hospital of Wuhan University as the team leader. The hospital has already accommodated 247 beds and will soon have 253 more. With emergency bed modifications, it will remain open to 800. Under the same arrangement, Wuchang's "Shelter Hospital" opposite the treatment of Wuchang District, Hongshan District and the Donghu New Technology Development Zone areas of mild cases confirmed patients.

February 4, Vulcan Mountain admitted the first batch of patients into the ward. Photo / Zhongqing newspaper Zhongqing Net, Li Jinzheng

At the same time, Kong Hon's Shelter Hospital in Wuhan International Convention and Exhibition Center and East West Lake Shelter Hospital in Wuhan Living Room were also completed.

Fu Angen, an employee of a real estate group in Wuhan who was originally involved in the construction of the Raytheon Mountain Hospital, was ordered to rush to the Wuhan Living Room and Wuhan International Convention and Exhibition Center shortly after 5 p.m. on February 3, and received the task of converting the exhibition into a shelter. This was the first time Angen knew about the 'shelter' and, by order, it had to be built the next day. Sanitation workers have begun to clear the site, he assembled the design team, at 1:00 on the 4th to draw up a renovation plan.

The contractor began to dispatch materials before the design scheme was formed. The materials also come from many sources: tables and benches were left over after the Wuhan Military Games, beds and bedding were dispatched from the Kong Hon district, and boards were ordered directly by the factory.

After 3 am, the first batch of materials arrived, Angen temporarily transferred about 200 carpenters and electricians, at 6 or 7 o'clock made the first ward model. Shortly after 8 am, the Wuhan Metro Group came to the rescue and the number of construction workers increased to 500. 4 p.m. , all baffles made; 10 p.m. , all switches and sockets installed.

At 2:30 a.m. on the 5th, after 33 hours, they finally delivered. Kong Hon's Shelter Hospital is co-ordinated by the Wuhan Union Hospital, with nine national medical teams and six Wuhan medical teams participating. In addition to the 1,600 beds, dozens of medical tents have been set up outside the hospital, according to a recent visit by China News Weekly.

Earlier on February 2, Vulcan Mountain Hospital has been officially delivered to the People's army medical workers. Six days later, on February 8, the hospital was ready for use. As of February 10, Huoshenshan hospital has received more than 800 patients transferred from the designated hospitals in Wuhan, the hospital has also started to receive patients, has been admitted more than 80 people. The new Mount Kinabalu Hospitals are entirely new, and many of their medical staff come from outside the country.

There are currently 107 medical teams and 10,596 medical personnel in Hubei Province to assist with medical treatment, Yang Yunyan, vice governor of Hubei Province, said at a press conference on the evening of February 6. "But there is still a serious shortage of medical staff, " he added.

Inside and outside the shelter

When the medical field in Wuhan fell into a "war famine and chaos" , medical teams from all over the country were massed one after another in Hubei. A video circulating on the Internet shows teams from Shandong Qilu Hospital and Sichuan Hwaseo hospital cheering each other across the aisle at Wuhan Tianhe Airport. These two hospitals are well-known, in the anti-japanese war period jointly run schools, medical services.

Wuhan's "WAR" will be more far into the entrapment, more and more medical workers into the flood of anti-epidemic, China's medical community no one seems to be able to stay completely out of the way. A few days of oaths, farewells, marches, and such scenes were on the doorstep of almost every major hospital in China.

When the shelter hospital is being constructed, the field medical staff who have arrived in Wuhan have not been idle. Wang Yishan, from the Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps, arrived in Wuhan in the early hours of June for training at the hotel. In order to reduce exposure and reduce the risk of infection, medical staff need to cut hair, male comrades borrow a push, their own shaved head, the lesbians cut the "hair. ". Some female colleagues are about to get married, crying will stay for a long time long hair cut.

The wear and tear process of protective equipment is complex and rigorous, and it is constantly changing. The medical staff needs to be trained to make sure that nothing goes wrong. Contact with a confirmed patient requires level three protection. This is the first time that Wang Yishan and Xie Rong, who were not originally from the infectious diseases department, have worn protective clothing.

During duty, the medical staff can not go to the toilet, or the whole set of protective equipment is out of action. "after more than 30 years, I put on a diaper again, " joked a doctor on duty in the show's shelter. In the shelter, medical staff usually wear a Adult diaper under their protective clothing. A nurse couldn't hold it in during her shift. After "solving the problem, " she had to stand, afraid to sit down again.

"Doctors are under a lot of pressure to work six-hour shifts, which is more tiring than standing for 10 hours, " Chen Xiaonan, vice-leader of the Hainan team, told China News Weekly. Add to that the fact that you have to wait in line for nine hours to get out of your Hazmat suit, and you don't eat or drink.

Chen Xiao man every time in the hotel to see just come back from the rotation of medical staff, one by one are drooping a head, the strength to speak are gone. Physical exertion is so great, some nurses come out, eat two boxes of rice. On Feb. 8, the day of the Lantern Festival, which also happened to be the birthday of Chen's teammates, the cake and the lantern were divided up and taken to their rooms to avoid infection after the routine protection training at 5 pm.

Medical staff have been put on standby, the surrounding streets began to co-ordinate the transfer of patients with mild illness from the isolation hotel to the shelter hospital. "collect what you want. " That's the assignment they got. Four patients from the Fangyingtai community were transferred to the Wuchang Shelter Hospital, where Yu Juan, the deputy secretary, later learned that the plan had been to move to another isolation point, and were not taken to the shelter hospital until two or three in the morning.

Streets in addition to the transfer of patients, but also to implement the "national temperature. ". On the morning of the 6th, Wuhan Outbreak Investigation Mobilization deployment will be held, requiring the "strength of the city" , door-to-door investigation of "four categories of personnel" , for "not a door, not a missing person. ". The order was issued from Wuhan to the streets and passed on to grass-roots communities.

At 4 o'clock on the afternoon of the 6th, Yu Juan received a notice from the street of Fruit Lake. According to the document spirit of "nationwide temperature measurement" , they need to go door-to-door, house-to-house investigation, a total of more than 5000 households. A body temperature above 37.3 C is the standard for fever.

Yu and her colleagues began to act, but soon ran into difficulties. The panic shut down the doors, the fear of contagion, the reluctance to see people. There are also some residents willing to cooperate with the work of the community, from afternoon to evening, the community completed the screening of 73 households. Yu Juan reflected the problem to the street.

The same experience has been experienced by workers in various grass-roots communities. In a community in Changfeng Street of Qiao Estuary, the director, Zhou Nianping, had to finish the investigation of more than 3000 households by 11:00 am the next day, together with the lower-ranking cadres who were paired up to help him. He could never fill out the report forms, which made his off-duty time delay again and again.

The construction of the shelter hospital alleviated the shortage of beds somewhat, but the trouble still existed. A patient waited in line for three hours at the door of a shelter hospital. When the patient's family returned, they smashed the door in the community to vent their frustration, to the dismay of Zhou.

In the baize community, Wang Lifen, deputy director of the grid, which has more than 300 residents, needs to complete more than 100 households the next morning. She didn't have time to eat, and she started vomiting. When I answered the phone, I sounded anxious, like I was a different person.

Yu Juan is also confused. The diagnosis of NCP is difficult. The onset of NCP is mild, even in mild cases without fever. "people are taking their temperature now, but it's not as if their temperature is normal and they don't have an infection. If they don't have a chest CT or a nucleic acid test, even a doctor might not be able to tell. " However, in reality, nor is it possible to do so for every Wuhan resident. But this kind of thinking, can only be put in the stomach. Right now, the first priority is to complete the work assigned by the organization. If we move too slowly, we will delay the battle against the pandemic.

By the next day, according to instructions from a superior, Yu Juan and her colleagues in the Fangyingtai community had changed their strategy, adopting a combination of online self-examination and door-to-door examination, and using wechat groups and Wechat neighborhoods, asking residents to submit temperature results on their own initiative. Other communities have largely adopted the same format. In addition to the original 7 staff, the City and district sent a group of cadres, dedicated to the community of living alone and empty nesters.

Noah's Ark

At 3 a.m. on Feb. 6, the Wembley Arena shelter hospital in Wuchang welcomed more than 90 patients who had been transferred from the hospital and community isolation points. To prevent cross contamination, the museum's air conditioning has been closed. It was cold in the middle of the night and it was raining in winter outside. Around the same time, the Kong Hon Shelter Hospital at the heart of the show began taking patients.

According to the official admission criteria, patients are transferred from the government to the shelter hospital. Only mild pneumonia patients under 65 years of age with no serious complications are admitted to the shelter hospital. But because the designated hospital bed is too tight, some communities will also send some seriously ill patients to the shelter hospital.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At 1:00 am that day, from Qiao estuary confirmed patient Zhao Zhiguo suddenly received a call from the community, said that the shelter hospital has vacated two beds. Zhao Zhiguo's special case, his 70-year-old mother also infected with the virus, is critically ill, and blind. Mother and son have been waiting at home, and there is no separation from the family. After the infection, Zhao Zhiguo immediately reported to the property, but their building door "no infection door hole" sign has not been amended.

After arriving at the Shelter Hospital, a staff member of the community advised him to say that his mother's age was lower and her condition milder. Zhao Zhiguo disagreed. He believed that his mother's condition was critical and that the conditions in the shelter hospital were simply not adequate to meet her medical needs. Toss until three or four in the morning, still under the rain, Zhao Zhiguo with his mother left the shelter. Two days later, he finally arrived at the designated hospital beds, his mother into the hospital, he was admitted to the Shelter Hospital.

The first morning, someone reported that the Wuchang Shelter Hospital "had no medicine, no heat, no electricity, no food" . In response, Li Qiang, Wuhan's deputy mayor, told China News Weekly: "We are working on a solution in accordance with the principle of territorial management, and we believe that the situation will soon be on the right track. " Li Qiang also stressed that, "As academician Wang Chen said, the shelter hospital is not a foolproof solution, but it is a more urgent and better choice. I firmly believe that. "

Xie said the problem of "No one to feed" had indeed arisen on the first morning of the patient's arrival at Wuchang's shelter hospital. She explained that because the patients'meals were placed in the clean area, the medical staff did not communicate well during the shift change and failed to bring in the boxed meals. "Once they enter the contaminated area, there is no going back, " they said, setting a rule that patients' boxed meals would be carried into the shelter by the next shift.

We have a similar situation at Kong Hon's Shelter Hospital. "On the first morning of my visit, I didn't give out any medicine. Everyone was in a big mood. Now we have food and drink, no air conditioning, but we have electric blankets so it's not too cold, " Xu Yingran, a patient, told China News Weekly, the medicine was given out in the afternoon, and everyone felt much calmer.

At Wuchang's shelter hospital, patients call each other "cabin mates. " . "Academician Wang Chen said that the shelter is a Noah's Ark ship. All those who come here take refuge, and the cabin crew share weal and woe, " said a patient named Huang Fengying, although anxiety still exists.

When you're sick, people are often moved by the usual things. Huang Fengying remember, a provincial women and children surnamed Wang Director, every visit, will try to make every patient laugh. Medical staff from Shandong Qilu Hospital have specially compiled a dialect handbook to reduce the communication barriers caused by the language. The spread of the epidemic has created too many gaps, especially psychological ones, that also need to be bridged. Over the past two days, some of the patients at the Shelter Hospital have started dancing in the square.

Outside the shelter, the vehicles carrying patients are still busy. Wang Jun, a driver from Tangjiadun street in Jianghan district, is as dangerous as the paramedics, wearing heavy protective clothing at all times and breathing hot air that turns into water on his mask.

Tangjiadun street is also home to the south China Seafood Market. The shelter is not foolproof, and the number of new community outposts is growing, Wang Jun said in an interview. A hotel on Tangjiadun street has just been vacated, and the government has expanded the scope of the requisition to include student dormitories at some universities.

Since the outbreak, Wang Jun has been traveling between designated hospitals, community quarantines and shelter hospitals. He was like a man on the battlefield, feeling the emotional and psychological changes of the people around him. In one case, he sent two patients with mild illness to a shelter hospital. "I'm going to stay in the community until there are beds in the designated hospital, " one patient said. Another patient advised him, "it's not right. The community is hard enough. "

The situation is changing from day to day. A clearer treatment process is starting to restore order to community work. Yu Juan, deputy director of the Fangyingtai community, told China News weekly that for confirmed and seriously ill patients, the community reports to the streets, the streets report to the district, unified arrangements for beds. Additional patients with mild illness were accommodated in the shelter hospital from the streets and the community, while close contacts were placed in community isolation points.

With the expansion of the Shelter Hospital and the community isolation point, the pressure of the grass-roots community is expected to be further eased. Four patients with mild illness from the Fangyingtai community were transferred to Wuchang's shelter hospital, but there were limited beds. In the last two days, additional confirmed cases have been transferred to the East West Lake Shelter Hospital, which has a capacity of 2,000 beds.

"The number of new cases is decreasing, which I think is a welcome sign. However, the number of cases accumulated earlier, so at present, there will be a time lag between the reduction in the number of new cases and the reduction in the number of patients seeking medical treatment,"Zhao Lei, chief physician of the Wuhan Union Hospital, told China Newsweek.

On February 9, communities across Wuhan were given "death orders" to admit all confirmed and suspected cases as soon as possible. In the official description, the operation "collect" has entered the stage of a general offensive.

(Wang Yishan, Zhou Nianping, Wang Lifen, Yu Juan, Wang Jun and Cheng Tianming were used as aliases at the request of the interviewees.)
